<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142252" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole crassicornis var. diversipilosa" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole crassicornis var. diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="crassicornis" variety="diversipilosa">Pheidole crassicornis var. diversipilosa Wheeler</taxonomicName>
1908h: 467. Raised to species level by Naves 1985: 61. Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="153">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diversipilosa">diversipilosa</taxonomicName>
, different (variable) hair, alluding to the major.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="153">
diagnosis Very close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33688" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">crassicornis</taxonomicName>
from which it differs in the major by abundant pilosity on the mesosoma and gaster, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181655" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tetra Creighton" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tetra Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetra">tetra</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs in the major by the much shorter pilosity on the first gastral tergite and by sparseness or absence of pilosity on the waist and occiput.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="153">
Also resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181652" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilosior Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pilosior Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosior">pilosior</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porcula">porcula</taxonomicName>
in various traits as depicted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="153">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.26, HL 1.34, SL 0.66, EL 0.20, PW 0.66. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.66, HL 0.74, SL 0.76, EL 0.16, PW 0.46. color Major and minor: body medium reddish brown, appendages light reddish brown. Range Southwestern Texas to the mountains of southern and central Arizona.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="153">
Biology According to Stefan Cover (personal communication), 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diversipilosa">diversipilosa</taxonomicName>
is common at mid-elevations (1050-1900 m), favoring oak-pine-juniper forests, especially those in creek valleys, where it nests under rocks and in open soil. Colonies have single queens and large populations, which can exceed 1000 workers. Seed caches have been found in some nests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
